Anonymous Wed 24 Jun 2020 20:18:08 No.31109153 Report
Quoted By:
>>31109075
like any skill you get better with time. also its remarkable how learning to write better also helps to organize your thoughts. its something psychologists consistently recommend to patients struggling to understand their own feelings and thoughts.

i don't think its a coincidence that some of the best speakers and orators are almost always very prolific writers too. even if they just wrote in private journals or in letters.

one advantage of the digital medium is stuff isn't set in stone. there may be advantages of committing pen to paper and dealing with that permanence, but it's also really nice to realize you need one sentence somewhere else and just be able to move it there, or take it out entirely, etc.

We've already discussed in depth just how radically sapience and bipedalism would change a species; chances are they'd see us blushing, scratching ourselves, sweating, not being covered in fur, and having flat faces as just as weird as we'd see the things that they do. Even then, the things they do wouldn't be anywhere near as extreme as we see in their current feral counterparts. We don't eat the bugs that we find on ourselves from scratching and we've developed things to minimize the negative parts of sweating. So why would dogs still eat their own vomit? Primates are extremely violent and promiscuous, yet humans are extremely kind and loyal, at least compared to most of the animal kingdom barring a few exceptions. There's decent reason to believe that a lot of anthros would be even less promiscuous or violent than modern humans are. What is it that makes you think having a real waifur would be awful?

The vehicle issue isn't really a problem. There's no serious need for the bottom of the seat-back to be flush with the back of the seat-bottom. It's not even important for transporting long things with the seat flipped down because it'd just bridge over the gap anyway. So, redesigning car seats simply to have a gap would be trivial.

Yeah, dietary stuff would be a potential challenge, because different animals would have different things they could or couldn't eat. But humans will eat damn near anything, so it's much more likely that other anthros would only be able to eat relatively limited selections of human food -- but in any event, if humans can eat more than monkeys, it wouldn't be surprising that evolved anthros would also tolerate a wider variety of things.

Ergonomics would differ, sure. But again, it's not a stretch that they'd evolve something a lot like fingers, in which case you could probably just swap keycaps on your keyboard and be good.

But the bottom line is, anthros aren't going to just materialize out of nowhere. In a universe like that, they'd have always been around, which means everything would have already been developed with versatility in mind. Have you seen some of the wacky early designs for typewriter keyboards? We'd simply have wound up with somewhat different-looking Stuff from the outset.

First off, convergent evolution is rather common when filling a common niche, all it would take would be more isolated humans and creatures needing to fill the niche. Lets say a NEW great dying occurs at the end of the bronze age, millions of years later the world is full of anthros and the resurgent humans.
Yes, ungulate derived anthros would likely have different hands wholesale, but less so with Avians, Reptiles, and digitigrade mammals where the hand structures already exist in an unrefined (or highly refined) way. Almost every creature is omnivorous in some way or another and they would likely become generalists like ourselves albeit with some restrictions here or there, but that would be as minor as a gluten free, vegan, or Kosher diet already.

I'm probably revealing way too much personal information since these things were super rare.

My current job still has some old mini-CNC tables.
The controller that sits between the computer and table uses an Intel 8080, and that's the upgrade. The original computer system was a custom CP/M machine that used two 8" floppies. One for the program, one for files. Two monitors; one for text, one for graphics.

Four serials per old ass P133 system. Tables still work as long as you keep the screws lubed.

Anonymous Thu 25 Jun 2020 02:17:46 No.31115777 Report

>>31115394
My only remaining CP/M box is a Osborne.

I'll drop another tibdit since you mentioned Macs.
Apple has to kiss Adobe's ass like a Muslim pointing himself to Mecca.
Back when Photoshop was really young and desktop publishing didn't exist yet, almost anything computer controlled was still on a maze of custom machines.
Now after Apple got rid of Jobs the first time they came out with the IIC line. More powerful in some respects than a contemporary PC of the time, but in the 8000 USD range for the base system.
Some assholes got the bright idea to market these to people still chugging along on 10+ year old equipment. Add on a nice monitor, couple extra add-on cards, and that's 15000 USD.

One problem. They didn't work. Largely it was the power supplies couldn't handle what they were being asked to do. That and the software made 70s era IBM look user friendly.
Apple didn't give a damn at the time, the card companies that packaged the crap failed.
So heaps of the higher end industrial machines that were small enough to be run from a desktop computer got rebuilt to use a PC as the frontend.

As for the PET, awesome. I have a 8032 that hasn't been fired up in a few years. Handful of other machines.
Those were the days, yessireebob-and-where's-my-monster? Binders of floppies, bound manuals, and formfeed printer paper.
My torture is explaining the MS/DOS command line to the morons that somehow escape the layout program. That, and that I can ssh into the box and see if they're keeping the machines running.
The worst was a kid that managed to escape that (which is supposed to respawn), close the xterm monitoring the jobs, and dropping himself from fluxbox to a bash shell that has no access to /bin or /sbin

Pays the bills.

To me the layout that makes the most sense is
>authoritarian = clear hierarchy where everyone has a role
>libertarian = lack of leader-follower hierarchy/everyone is equal
>left = supportive/protective relationships
>right = might makes right/meritocratic relationships

This leads to:
>ants are authleft (everyone has their place but everyone is "equal", everyone fulfills their natural role)
>lions are authright (leader-follower hierarchy but weaklings get wrecked even if they're former leaders)
>sheep are libleft (protective herd mentality, but no clear "alphas" and no clear division of roles)
>cats are libright (self-centered and self-reliant)
